\parindent 0pt \parskip 6pt
\vspace{-10pt}

In {\tt wvs-048}, I assumed that the heights, say $H(\zeta,\phi)$, that
are represented by the height reference array $H_{ij}$ that is output
from the hydrostatic calculation are piecewise-linear functions in
$\phi$.  That is, for constant $\zeta$ and $\phi_j \leq \phi \leq
\phi_{j+1}$,
$H(\zeta,\phi) = H(\zeta,\phi_j) +
                 \frac{\partial H}{\partial \phi} (\phi-\phi_j)$
where $\frac{\partial H}{\partial \phi}$ is assumed to be piecewise constant, or
$H = \frac{H_{i,j+1}-H_{ij}}
          {(\phi_{j+1}-\phi_t)-(\phi_j-\phi_t)} (\phi-\phi_t)$.
This led to a requirement to solve

\begin{equation}
H_{ij} + \frac{H_{i,j+1}-H_{ij}}
              {(\phi_{j+1}-\phi_t)-(\phi_j-\phi_t)}
                  ((\phi-\phi_t)-(\phi_j-\phi_t))
                        - H_t
= (H_t+R^\oplus_{\text{eq}})(\sec (\phi-\phi_t) - 1)
\end{equation}

for $\phi$ (notice that $R^\oplus_{\text{eq}}$ cancels on the left side).

Assuming instead that the heights are piecewise-linear functions of
sec$(\phi)$, and writing

\begin{equation}\begin{split}
s =\,& \sec(\phi-\phi_t) - 1\\
s_j =\,& \sec(\phi_j-\phi_t) - 1 \\
s_{j+1} =\,& \sec(\phi_{j+1}-\phi_t) - 1 \\
f =\,& \frac{H_{i,j+1}-H_{ij}}
            {\sec(\phi_{j+1}-\phi_t)-\sec(\phi_j-\phi_t)} =
       \frac{H_{i,j+1}-H_{ij}}
            {s_{j+1}-s_j} \\
\end{split}\end{equation}

we find a need instead to solve

\begin{equation}
H_{ij} + f ( s - s_j ) - H_t = (H_t+R^\oplus_{\text{eq}}) s
\end{equation}

from which

\begin{equation}
s = \sec(\phi-\phi_t) - 1 =
    \frac{H_{ij} - H_t - f s_j}
         {H_t+R^\oplus_{\text{eq}} - f}
\text{ or }
s+1 = \sec(\phi-\phi_t) =
    \frac{H_{ij} + R^\oplus_{\text{eq}} - f (s_j+1)}
         {H_t+R^\oplus_{\text{eq}} - f}
    \,.
\end{equation}

This is far simpler, and doesn't require an iteration.

1.  Is it worth trying?

2.  Should $R^\oplus_{\text{eq}}$ be $R^\oplus_{\text{eq}} -
H_{\text{surf}}$ throughout?

